In article <lehimes.760667233@access3>, lehimes@access3.digex.net (Larry Himes) writes:
> asb@cs.nott.ac.uk (Andrew Brown) writes:
> 
> 
> >Each block in the fs (1024 bytes) is encrypted as an independent unit,
> >using the key and IV generated above using IDEA in CBC mode. This
> >means that identical blocks will encipher to identical ciphertext - is
> >this a problem ?
> 
> A better technique would be to vary the IV using the "sector id" of the 
> block in some way. This could be an actual hardware cyl/track/sector address
> or a relative address such as block number.

Yes, in CBC mode the IV needs to be kept secret anyway, so
why not just calculate the IV by encrypting the sector id
added mod 2^64 to the constant IV you already have? The key
could be the passphrase derived block encryption key, for
instance.

> 
> Larry..

